        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down Farnborough Kent</placeName>
                    <date>March 17<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>—</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
<p>I write a line merely to thank you for your <hi rend="underline">very complete</hi> information regarding M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Hanley’s residence. I will certainly visit him when next I stay in London; but London unfortunately always disagrees with my health. I enclose with many thanks <hi rend="underline">stamps</hi> (which I hope will not be inconvenient) for Eling’s specimen.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>Yours very sincerely | C. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
                <div type="tnotes">
                    <note xml:id="tnote.n1">1.4 (which] <hi rend="italic">after del</hi> ‘for’</note>
                </div>

        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The date is confirmed by a copy of the letter in DAR 143, in which the copyist recorded a postmark: ‘March 18<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>., <hi rend="italic">1850</hi>.’</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-1310.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to J. S. Bowerbank, [8 March 1850]</ref>.</note>
        </div>        
            
